00:00:54.690 --> 00:00:57.020

        Narrator:
        IN A SOCIETY AS DIVERSE AS OURS,
      

00:00:57.020 --> 00:01:00.830

        THERE ARE SITUATIONS THAT MANY
        PEOPLE CONSIDER TO BE UNFAIR,
      

00:01:00.830 --> 00:01:05.400

        UNACCEPTABLE OR UNENDURABLE.


00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:07.570

        THESE PEOPLE MAY JOIN TOGETHER


00:01:07.570 --> 00:01:10.240

        IN SPONTANEOUS
        OR ORGANIZED ACTIVITIES
      

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:12.640

        TO GAIN POWER AND SEEK SOLUTIONS


00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:17.240

        THROUGH COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
        AND SOCIAL ACTION.
      

00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:19.550

        SOCIOLOGISTS STUDY
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
      

00:01:19.550 --> 00:01:22.750

        BECAUSE OF ITS INFLUENCE
        ON SOCIAL CHANGE.
      

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:24.250

        SUCH CHANGE OFTEN BEGINS


00:01:24.250 --> 00:01:27.090

        WITH THE ISOLATED ACTIONS
        OF INDIVIDUALS
      

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:36.160

        AND GROWS INTO
        ORGANIZED SOCIAL MOVEMENTS.
      

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:44.970

        ( Xylophone Music )


00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:46.970

        RALLIES,


00:01:46.970 --> 00:01:49.110

        FADS,


00:01:49.110 --> 00:01:51.310

        RIOTS,


00:01:51.310 --> 00:01:53.810

        PUBLIC CELEBRATIONS,


00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:55.920

        STRIKES.


00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:59.120

        WHAT DO THESE SOCIAL EVENTS
        HAVE IN COMMON?
      

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:02.490

        THEY ALL EXHIBIT
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR.
      

00:02:02.490 --> 00:02:03.790

        Tracey McKenzie Elliott:
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
      

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:08.890

        REFERS TO A CONTINUUM OF
        NON-ROUTINE, UNUSUAL BEHAVIORS
      

00:02:08.890 --> 00:02:11.560

        ENGAGED IN
        BY LARGE NUMBERS OF PEOPLE.
      

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:14.070

        THESE BEHAVIORS ARE UNUSUAL
        AND NON-ROUTINE
      

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:15.270

        BECAUSE THEY'RE NOT GOVERNED


00:02:15.270 --> 00:02:17.770

        BY THE TYPICAL,
        EVERYDAY SOCIAL NORMS
      

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:21.210

        THAT USUALLY
        SHAPE SOCIAL LIFE IN ACTION.
      

00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:23.040

        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR


00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:26.110

        IS REALLY A CONTINUUM


00:02:26.110 --> 00:02:28.350

        OF NON-ROUTINE BEHAVIORS


00:02:28.350 --> 00:02:30.680

        THAT DON'T OCCUR EVERY DAY,


00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:33.620

        THAT ARE OFTEN
        VERY EXTRAORDINARY,
      

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:35.690

        THAT ARE ENGAGED IN


00:02:35.690 --> 00:02:38.460

        BY A RELATIVELY
        LARGE NUMBER OF PEOPLE.
      

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:42.060

        ( Crowd Voices )


00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:45.130

        Narrator:
        AT ONE END OF THE CONTINUUM
	OF COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
      

00:02:45.130 --> 00:02:47.400

        IS THE SPONTANEOUS
        BEHAVIOR OF PEOPLE
      

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:50.470

        WHO REACT TO SITUATIONS
        THEY PERCEIVE AS UNCERTAIN
      

00:02:50.470 --> 00:02:53.910

        OR THREATENING,
        AS IN A RIOT,
      

00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:56.540

        OR SITUATIONS
        THAT ARE EXTREMELY ATTRACTIVE,
      

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:59.710

        LIKE A MARDI GRAS CELEBRATION.


00:02:59.710 --> 00:03:01.650

        William Kornblum:
        BY SPONTANEOUS
	COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR,
      

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:06.720

        WE REALLY MEAN BEHAVIOR
        THAT'S NOT PLANNED
      

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:09.820

        AND NOT ORGANIZED BEFOREHAND


00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:13.990

        IT SEEMS TO OCCUR
        VERY UNEXPECTEDLY.
      

00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:15.130

        Richard Scotch:
        WE CAN SEE
      

00:03:15.130 --> 00:03:16.760

        WHEN PEOPLE GATHER TOGETHER


00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:19.630

        AND SOMETHING HAPPENS THAT
        PEOPLE PERCEIVE AS THREATENING,
      

00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:22.200

        THEY OFTEN WILL RESPOND IN FEAR.


00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:25.640

        THEY LOOK AROUND TO OTHERS TO
        TRY TO FIND OUT WHAT'S GOING ON,
      

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:29.070

        OR WHAT KIND OF RESPONSE
        IS APPROPRIATE.
      

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:30.410

        IN SOME CIRCUMSTANCES,


00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:32.850

        PEOPLE REMAIN CALM
        IN THE FACE OF FEAR,
      

00:03:32.850 --> 00:03:35.510

        AND IN OTHER RESPONSES,
        THEY SIMPLY PANIC.
      

00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:38.820

        AND PEOPLE MIGHT STAMPEDE
        FOR THE EXIT OF A BUILDING,
      

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:41.120

        AND MANY PEOPLE ARE HURT.


00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:44.490

        Protesters:
        PEACEFULLY ASSEMBLE,
	PEACEFULLY ASSEMBLE ...
      

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:46.190

        Narrator:
        AT THE OTHER END
	OF THE CONTINUUM
      

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:49.330

        OF COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
        ARE PLANNED, ORGANIZED EVENTS,
      

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:53.370

        LIKE RALLIES, DEMONSTRATIONS,
        PROTEST MEETINGS OR FESTIVALS.
      

00:03:53.370 --> 00:03:55.430

        ( Bagpipe Music )


00:03:55.430 --> 00:03:58.570

        WHY DO SOCIOLOGISTS
        EXPLORE COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR?
      

00:03:58.570 --> 00:04:01.070

        WHAT DO THEY HOPE TO DISCOVER?


00:04:01.070 --> 00:04:03.640

        William Kornblum:
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
	HAS LONG TRADITIONS
      

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:05.410

        OF BEING STUDIED
        BY SOCIOLOGISTS,
      

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:07.680

        BECAUSE
        FROM COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR,
      

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:11.520

        WE OFTEN GET THE BEGINNINGS
        OF VERY IMPORTANT SOCIAL CHANGES
      

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:13.590

        IN THE SOCIETY.


00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:17.520

        SO WHEN CROWDS
        REACT IN CERTAIN WAYS
      

00:04:17.520 --> 00:04:22.030

        OR WHEN PEOPLE EXPRESS
        THEMSELVES IN UNUSUAL FORMS,
      

00:04:22.030 --> 00:04:24.760

        SOCIOLOGISTS KNOW THAT
        THAT'S OFTEN THE BEGINNING
      

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:27.730

        OF SOME EVENTS
        THAT WILL TAKE PLACE
      

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:31.540

        THAT COULD RESULT
        IN VERY IMPORTANT CHANGE.
      

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:33.170

        Tracey McKenzie Elliott:
        SOCIOLOGISTS,
      

00:04:33.170 --> 00:04:34.970

        WHEN STUDYING
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR,
      

00:04:34.970 --> 00:04:39.410

        ATTEMPT TO DISCOVER AND IDENTIFY
        UNDER WHAT CONDITIONS
      

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:42.050

        CERTAIN TYPES
        OF COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR ARISE
      

00:04:42.050 --> 00:04:44.380

        AND WHETHER THIS
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
      

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.450

        WILL DEVELOP INTO
        A SOCIAL MOVEMENT OR NOT.
      

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:51.060

        Richard Scotch:
        SOMETIMES COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR
	IS JUST BLOWING OFF STEAM,
      

00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:53.590

        BUT IN OTHER CASES,
        IT IS THE BEGINNING
      

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:58.100

        OF LONG-TERM ATTEMPTS
        TO CHANGE SOCIETY.
      

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:01.300

        ( Music Playing )


00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:05.100

        Narrator:
        TO UNDERSTAND AND PREDICT
	SPONTANEOUS COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR,
      

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:08.470

        SOME SOCIOLOGISTS USE A TOOL
        DEVELOPED BY JOHN LOFLAND,
      

00:05:08.470 --> 00:05:12.880

        CALLED THE TYPOLOGY OF
        SPONTANEOUS COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR.
      

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:16.750

        BY EXAMINING THE STRUCTURE
        AND MOTIVATING EMOTIONS,
      

00:05:16.750 --> 00:05:20.420

        SOCIOLOGISTS IDENTIFY
        SIMILARITIES AND DIFFERENCES
      

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:22.920

        AMONG COLLECTIVE BEHAVIORS.


00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:25.720

        WHEN LOOKING AT THE STRUCTURE
        OF COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR,
      

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:27.390

        SOCIOLOGISTS FIRST DISTINGUISH


00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:30.430

        BETWEEN A "CROWD"
        AND A "MASS" OF PEOPLE.
      

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:31.830

        Tracey McKenzie Elliott:
        IN A CROWD,
      

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:34.570

        PEOPLE ARE
        IN CLOSE PHYSICAL PROXIMITY
      

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:35.870

        TO ONE ANOTHER.


00:05:35.870 --> 00:05:37.300

        IN A MASS,


00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:40.670

        THE GROUP IS DISPERSED
        ACROSS A GEOGRAPHICAL AREA.
      

00:05:40.670 --> 00:05:43.480

        A MASS IS ALSO
        A LARGE NUMBER OF PEOPLE,
      

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:45.780

        BUT THEY'RE NOT NECESSARILY
        IN EACH OTHER'S PRESENCE.
      

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:48.250

        THEY'RE ALL ORIENTED
        IN A CERTAIN WAY.
      

00:05:48.250 --> 00:05:50.250

        Dick Clark:
        THE BALL IS BEGINNING TO MOVE...
      

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:54.150

        William Kornblum:
        THEY MAY BE WATCHING
	A SIMILAR TELEVISION SHOW,
      

00:05:54.150 --> 00:05:58.060

        WATCHING THE NEW YEAR'S EVE
        CELEBRATION.
      

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:00.590

        Dick Clark:
        ...3, 2, 1.
      

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:02.800

        HAPPY 2000!


00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:04.630

        ( Crowd Cheers )


00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:07.570

        William Kornblum:
        THE PEOPLE GATHERED
	IN TIMES SQUARE ARE A CROWD.
      

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:12.640

        THE PEOPLE WATCHING
        ON TELEVISION ARE A MASS.
      

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:14.170

        Narrator:
        IN LOFLAND'S CHART,
      

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:17.280

        THE PRIMARY MOTIVATING EMOTIONS
        OF THE PEOPLE INVOLVED
      

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:22.850

        INCLUDE FEAR, HOSTILITY AND JOY.


00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:24.780

        THE INTERSECTION
        OF THE TWO FACTORS,
      

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:27.150

        STRUCTURE AND
        MOTIVATING EMOTION,
      

00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:29.090

        GIVES SOCIOLOGISTS
        A CLEARER PICTURE
      

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:32.660

        OF SPONTANEOUS
        COLLECTIVE BEHAVIOR.
      

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:34.390

        AN EXAMPLE IS WHAT HAPPENS


00:06:34.390 --> 00:06:38.230

        WHEN THE EMOTION OF FEAR
        INTERSECTS WITH A CROWD.
      

00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:40.230

        ( Alarm Ringing )


00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:41.670

        COME ON, LET'S GO!


00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:43.700

        GET OUT THE DOOR--
        THEY'RE CLOSING THE DOOR!
      

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:45.100

        William Kornblum:
        THE ORDERLINESS OF SOCIETY
      

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:46.640

        IS BASED ON A LOT
        OF VERY SMALL NORMS
      

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:49.170

        WE DON'T NECESSARILY
        ALWAYS PAY ATTENTION TO,
      

00:06:49.170 --> 00:06:51.080

        LIKE WHEN
        A LARGE GROUP OF PEOPLE
      

00:06:51.080 --> 00:06:53.410

        ARE TRYING TO GET THROUGH
        A SMALLER EXIT,
      

00:06:53.410 --> 00:06:55.110

        WE LET EACH OTHER TAKE TURNS.


00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:57.120

        WE DON'T GET MAD IF SOMEBODY
        STEPS IN FRONT OF US,
      

00:06:57.120 --> 00:07:00.490

        BECAUSE WE KNOW WE HAVE TO STEP
        IN FRONT OF SOMEBODY ELSE.
      

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:03.090

        Crewman:
        ORDER!
	KEEP ORDER HERE!
      

00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:06.460

        William Kornblum:
        WHEN FEAR MOTIVATES
	THAT SAME GROUP OF PEOPLE,
      

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:10.000

        THEY VIOLATE THOSE NORMS
        AND ALL PRESS FOR THE EXIT
      

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:11.730

        AND SHOULDER EACH OTHER
        OUT OF THE WAY,
      

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:13.030

        AND THE WEAKER ONES FALL DOWN


00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:14.770

        AND MAY GET TRAMPLED
        BY THE OTHERS.
      

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:18.270

        Crewman:
        GET BACK, I SAY!
      

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:21.710

        William Kornblum:
        AN EXAMPLE OF A MASS
	BEING DRIVEN BY FEAR
      

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:24.140

        HAS TO DO WITH
        THE FINANCIAL MARKETS.
      

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:26.410

        ( Bell Clanging )


00:07:26.410 --> 00:07:32.480

        MASSES OF PEOPLE OWN SECURITIES,
        MUTUAL FUNDS, STOCKS AND BONDS.
      

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:36.690

        WHEN THEY FEAR SUDDENLY THAT
        THE MARKET IS LOSING ITS VALUE
      

00:07:36.690 --> 00:07:40.360

        BECAUSE THE VALUE OF STOCKS
